of peace-keeping, to peacebuilding, humanitarian intervention, war-affected children, international humanitarian law, the International Criminal Court, the economic agendas of conflict, transnational crime, and the emergence of connectivity and a global civil society, the authors offer new insights into the importance of considering these issues as part of a single agenda. Human Security and the New Diplomacy is a case-study of a major Canadian foreign policy initiative and a detailed account of the first phase of the human security agenda. The story of Canada's leading role in promoting a humanitarian approach to international relations, it will be of interest to foreign policy specialists and students alike. Contributors include David Angell, Alan Bones, Michael Bonser, Terry Cormier, Patricia Fortier, Bob Fowler, Elissa Goldberg, Mark Gwozdecky, Sam Hanson, Paul Heinbecker, Eric Hoskins, Don Hubert, David Lee, Dan Livermore, Jennifer Loten, Rob McRae, Valerie Ooterveld, Victor Rakmil, Darryl Robinson, Jill Sinclair, Michael Small, Ross Snyder, Carmen Sorger, and Roman Waschuk.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBien-être. 0aConflict management. 0aHumanitarian intervention. 0aIntervention (Droit international). 0aIntervention (International law). 0aPaix. 0aPeace. 0aPeacekeeping forces. 0aSecurity, International. 0aSécurité internationale. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh1 aAngell, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnnan, Kofi A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAxworthy, Lloyd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBones, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonser, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorm